<br>
On Jan. 7, the Times printed yet another letter on nuclear power from Kenneth C. Kerns, the emergency response coordinator at Iowa State University. He states that “nuclear plants, an economic pariah just a few years ago, are now hallmarks for success for electric utilities.”<br>
.<br>
… Certainly everyone by now understands that nuclear power is an unviable option. … <br>
.<br>
Has a way been found to neutralize radioactive nuclear waste that has a half-life of thousands of years? Of course not. Can anyone envision that ever happening? Of course not.<br>
.<br>
One wonders what Mr. Kerns would say about the near-disaster in Ohio recently. A Jan. 4 Toledo Blade story about the Davis-Besse nuclear plant in Oak Harbor, Ohio, said, “… Two cavities in the reactor head caused by leaking boric acid, one so deep that six inches of steel had been melted down to a quarter-inch liner so thin that its strength was not known.<br>
.<br>
… Amazingly, it appears that the Nuclear Regulatory Agency put kilowatt production and company profits ahead of safety. A Jan. 7 New York Times editorial said, “regulatory staff was slow to order Davis-Besse to shut down for inspection, in large part because it did not want to impose unnecessary costs on the owner and did not want to give the industry a black eye.”<br>
.<br>
Future generations of Americans will have a huge and potentially unmanageable problem with our nuclear waste. … What we need to do is to stop making more nuclear waste. Now. <br>
.<br>
Don Paulson<br>
.<br>
Letts, Iowa <br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Hot damn. It must be easy getting a letter published at QCTimes.com. Either that or they are raving tree huggers who can't resist printing anything that bashes nuclear power no matter how ignorant. I'll give it a go and find out. First I need to look up some FAS pages on the history of breeder reactors. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 828<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/5/03 1:59:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Anti-Nuclear Letter to the Editor.</span><hr size=1> They probably just can't stop publishing the luddites who want to turn back the clock on human civilization until no one but themselves are left to run things.  I found this excerpt from the article interesting:<br>
<br>
&quot;“nuclear plants, an economic pariah just a few years ago, are now hallmarks for success for electric utilities.”&quot;<br>
<br>
Hmmm, economic pariah?  I find it amusing how people like the author clamor to slap a billion tons of expensive red tape on nuclear power plants and then smugly tell us that &quot;nuclear plants are uneconomical.&quot;  If it's true that it's cheaper to run a nuke plant now than a few years go then there must have been some regulatory changes--which means something is finally going right! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 116<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/5/03 8:33:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Anti-Nuclear Letter to the Editor.</span><hr size=1> &quot;Certainly everyone by now understands that nuclear power is an unviable option.&quot;<br>
<br>
Really?  Everyone?  I'd like to see a statistic about this considering just over 50% of the US actually favors nuclear energy today.<br>
<br>
&quot;Has a way been found to neutralize radioactive nuclear waste that has a half-life of thousands of years? Of course not. Can anyone envision that ever happening? Of course not.&quot;<br>
<br>
This statement is utterly false.  We have two options for getting rid of nuclear waste. <br>
<br>
1) Most of the real long half-life stuff comes in the form of transuranic elements (i.e. Plutonium, Americium, etc.), Iodine, and Technetium making up 1% of fuel.  Spent fuel rods can be reprocessed so the dangerous stuff can be removed.  The fuel rod can be re-enriched and recycled and made to undergo fisson.  The plutonium can simply be burned in fission plants.<br>
<br>
2) The remaining radioactive fission fragments tend to not have as long half lives as the transuranics and can be stored safely for several hundred years.  This is well within the capabilities of modern engineering.  However, if this is not good enough, there is a technology called nuclear transmutation which shoots neutrons or protons at nuclear waste causing the waste particles themselves to undergo fission, reducing the problem.  The remaining uranium can be buried and is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>less radioactive</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> than normal uranium ore.<br>
<br>
Although this technology is decades off before becoming economically feasible, this is a far cry from the &quot;never&quot; that the author states.  If the author wants to argue transmutation will never be feasible, he should present some evidence to the effect.  Otherwise the author should stop stroking his own ideology and quit making ignorant blanket statements that are false.  <br>
<br>
&quot;One wonders what Mr. Kerns would say about the near-disaster in Ohio recently. A Jan. 4 Toledo Blade story about the Davis-Besse nuclear plant in Oak Harbor, Ohio, said, “...Two cavities in the reactor head caused by leaking boric acid, one so deep that six inches of steel had been melted down to a quarter-inch liner so thin that its strength was not known...Amazingly, it appears that the Nuclear Regulatory Agency put kilowatt production and company profits ahead of safety. A Jan. 7 New York Times editorial said, “regulatory staff was slow to order Davis-Besse to shut down for inspection, in large part because it did not want to impose unnecessary costs on the owner and did not want to give the industry a black eye.&quot;<br>
<br>
There were many warning signs that should have been followed.  The material buildup in the filters at the plants alone should have given away the problem.  Of course hindsight is 20/20, but the plant managers acted poorly and we should not tolerate such incompetence.<br>
<br>
However, does the existence of a few bad cops compel us to strike the entire police force?  Of course not.  We try to reform it.  The reason the NRC was slow to call for the inspection was the plant was due to undergo a revamp within the next year or so anyway.  Rather than shut the plant down twice, the NRC felt it to be safe to only have the plant shut down once.  Like I said, hindsight is 20/20.  However, this example does not invalidate the whole system, it just means we need to change our regulations and find new plant managers.<br>
<br>
Besides, no one died or was harmed because of this.  Also, no one would have died or been harmed had we had the worst case scenario.  The plant was built to withstand this.  I guess we are lucky, and we can learn from this without an accident.  However, if there was, everyone would still be alive and the world would go on.<br>
<br>
